ducts into mineral-bearing surface pools. (Ring & Miller, 1984; Gargaud et al., 2022)"}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Strecker formation of valine aminonitrile from isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_004", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "borate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "not reported", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "NH3/NH4+ and HCN/CN- in aqueous or mixed aqueous medium", "aqueous": true, "other": "Near-neutral to mildly basic/acidic window not valine-specifically resolved; cyanide-bearing pond or evaporative lagoon context"}, "mechanism": "Aldehyde imine/iminium formation with ammonia is trapped by cyanide to yield the alpha-aminonitrile precursor to valine.", "reasoning": "This reaction is directly retained as VAL-R1 in the evidence bundle: isobutyraldehyde + NH3/NH4+ + HCN/CN- gives valine aminonitrile. No valine-specific numeric yield was recovered, so this route is source-supported but not yield-backed. Mineral agents reflect plausible evaporitic/surface concentration contexts and are not claimed as literature-proven catalysts for valine-specific yield enhancement. (Strecker reaction and alpha-aminonitriles, 2018; Gargaud et al., 2022; Prebiotic syntheses of vitamin coenzymes II, J. Mol. Evol. source context)"}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "378K (105 \u00b0C) laboratory hydrolysis analogue", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "water; acidic laboratory hydrolysis analogue", "aqueous": true, "other": "Prebiotic hydrolysis conditions unresolved; 24 h analogue retained from source context"}, "mechanism": "Sequential nitrile hydration and amidic hydrolysis converts the alpha-aminonitrile into the free amino acid valine.", "reasoning": "This is VAL-R2 in the evidence bundle, the second half of the Strecker 