\n      \"name\": \"Spark discharge with isobutane feed generating valine precursors\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_002\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~25 \u00b0C bulk flask; localized spark much hotter\",\n        \"pressure\": \"N2 80 torr; hydrocarbon 150 torr; water vapor ~25 torr\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electric spark; tungsten electrodes; NH4Cl aqueous trap\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"0.05 M NH4Cl adjusted to pH 8.7 with ~1 mL 1 M NaOH; post-run 3 M HCl hydrolysis in experiment; literature interpretation links high valine yield to oxidation toward isobutyraldehyde hydrate followed by Strecker chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Energetic discharge in a reducing atmosphere generates reactive carbon and nitrogen species that accumulate cyanide and branched aldehyde precursors in the aqueous trap.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the best-supported valine family in the evidence bundle. Ring & Miller report the isobutane discharge as the strongest valine-producing experiment and interpret the enhanced valine production as arising through oxidation to isobutyraldehyde hydrate followed by Strecker synthesis. The network represents the precursor-generating stage rather than collapsing the entire experiment into a single direct valine step, addressing prior overcompression concerns (Ring & Miller, 1984, Table I isobutane experiment row). Mineral agents are included to satisfy the required surface-reaction schema, but they are contextual concentrative/photocatalytic surfaces rather than claimed experimental catalysts.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark discharge with methane feed generating cyanide and branched aldehyde precursors\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\", \"