les, 2018, Tetrahedron; Gargaud et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Shock synthesis in reduced gas mixture generating valine precursors\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"transient high-T shock; exact value not extracted\",\n        \"pressure\": \"transient high-P shock; exact value not extracted\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"shock wave energy\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"impact/shock chemistry in primitive atmosphere or atmosphere-ocean interface\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Shock energy in reduced gas mixtures generates reactive fragments and condensable organics that can furnish cyanide-bearing species and branched aldehyde precursors.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The evidence bundle retains shock synthesis as qualitatively suggestive for valine but without recovered valine-specific yield. To avoid the earlier mistake of overassigning direct valine production, this reaction is restricted to precursor generation feeding the established Strecker branch (Bar-Nun et al., 1970, as summarized in Ring & Miller, 1984; source-list context).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"VUV photochemistry of mixed ices generating precursor residue\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"10\u201380 K irradiation; warm-up to room temperature; hydrolysis 105 \u00b0C for 24 h in analytical workflow\",\n        \"pressure\": \"static vacuum ~10^-5 mbar during residue handling\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"VUV photons; acid hydrolysis in workflow; MgF2 or Cu substrates depending on experiment\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"interstellar/cometary ice analogue residue; valine-specific support weaker than route-family support\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photolysis of mixed ices produces complex organic residues containing amino-acid precursor functionality; upon warming and hydrolytic workup, cyanide/aldehyde-accessible precursor pools may be generated.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature retains this route as a weak/contested valine-specific family. To stay aligned with the evidence and prior feedback, the network does not overclaim direct valine or aminonitrile output. Instead it assigns an uncertain precursor-generating role linking ice photochemistry to the Strecker branch (Nuevo et al., 2008; Bernstein et al., 2002; Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al., 2002).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate formation in branched \u03b1-ketoacid feeder context\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent to hydrothermal fringe context; included as upstream feeder context rather than valine-specific demonstrated synthesis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-mediated CO2 reduction and carbon fixation chemistry provides \u03b1-ketoacid-like feedstock context, represented here by pyruvate as the accepted upstream node for branched ketoacid networks.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research bundle specifically identifies a 'pyruvate-derived branched \u03b1-ketoacid network' as an upstream feeder to 2-ketoisovalerate, but not as a demonstrated valine-forming route. This hydrothermal node is therefore included conservatively as contextual network interconnection, not as a claim of secure direct valine synthesis. The hydrothermal role is subordinated to the literature caution that hydrothermal settings may often destroy free valine rather than produce it (Liu et al., 2022; valine_ketoisovalerate_amination_sources.json pathway context; Kobayashi et al., 2010; ChemSusChem review, 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Conversion from pyruvate-derived branched \u03b1-ketoacid network to 2-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"not reported\",\n        \"pressure\": \"not reported\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"not reported\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"represented as inferred pathway context from pyruvate-derived branched \u03b1-ketoacid network\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Abstracted network step linking the accepted pyruvate-derived branched \u03b1-ketoacid feeder system to 2-ketoisovalerate as the immediate \u03b1-ketoacid precursor of valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research bundle explicitly retains 'pyruvate-derived branched \u03b1-ketoacid network' as upstream feeder context to KIV and flags it as an inferred link. This reaction is therefore necessary to connect the documented KIV amination hypothesis to the broader network, and is marked as contextual rather than directly demonstrated under prebiotic conditions (Liu et al., 2022; valine_ketoisovalerate_amination_sources.json pathway sources).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"\u03b1-Ketoacid amination of 2-ketoisovalerate to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"not reported\",\n        \"pressure\": \"not reported\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"cyanate in general \u03b1-ketoacid route; possible reducing equivalents/dinucleotide-like catalysts discussed\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"metabolism-like aqueous network or non-extreme hydrothermal fringe; yield not reported\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrogen incorporation into the \u03b1-ketoacid framework of 2-ketoisovalerate yields valine via nonenzymatic reductive amination/transamination-like chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This route is retained in the bundle as mechanistically attractive but not directly demonstrated prebiotically for valine with measured yield. It is therefore included as a literature-carried direct route to the target, with uncertainty preserved explicitly (Liu et al., 2022; Drotman et al., 1972; 2021 Life computational analysis cited in the bundle).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Dry high-pressure oligomerization of valine to valine-rich peptides\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"150\u2013200 \u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"50\u2013150 MPa\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none reported\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"non-aqueous solid-state/dehydrating; deep prebiotic marine sediments undergoing diagenesis; 48\u2013192 h\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Thermal condensation under dry high-pressure conditions links valine monomers into oligomeric products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The evidence bundle treats this as a downstream sink/assembly route from valine rather than a productive route to free valine, and prior feedback emphasized that distinction. It is therefore included only as fate chemistry after valine formation (Furukawa, Otake, Ishiguro, Nakazawa & Kakegawa, 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal degradation of valine in subcritical water\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"290\u2013330 \u00b0C\",\n        \"pressure\": \"subcritical water conditions; exact P not extracted\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"hot compressed water\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"hydrothermal high-temperature aqueous sink; degradation kinetics reported but numeric rate constants not extracted in bundle\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Subcritical-water exposure degrades free valine, constraining survivability in hot hydrothermal systems; the product pool is represented abstractly here by return to simpler carbonyl/carboxylate network context through pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature bundle retains hydrothermal degradation as a constraint route and specifically raises the open question of whether hydrothermal systems net-produce valine or mostly destroy it. This reaction is included to satisfy environmental interconnection while following the evidence that hydrothermal conditions are primarily destructive for free valine. The pyruvate output is an abstract network reconnection, so this product assignment is speculative but necessary to avoid an isolated sink node and is explicitly used only as simplified degraded carbonyl context (Kobayashi, Takase & Adachi, 2010; ChemSusChem review, 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface concentration and cyanide regeneration feeding Strecker chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\