nce >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Valine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network is anchored to the literature-supported valine routes in the provided evidence bundle. The strongest productive routes are the two yield-backed spark-discharge experiments of Ring & Miller (1984), represented as precursor-generating atmospheric plasma reactions feeding branched-aldehyde/Strecker chemistry and final hydrolysis to valine. Additional retained literature routes are included as lower-confidence but source-supported branches: generic Strecker formation from isobutyraldehyde, shock chemistry as a precursor-generating route, mixed-ice VUV photochemistry as a weak/contested precursor route, and \u03b1-ketoacid amination from 2-ketoisovalerate as a mechanistically attractive but unresolved direct route. Hydrothermal chemistry is handled conservatively in line with the research findings: hydrothermal environments contribute network interconnection through pyruvate/fringe ketoacid context and, more securely, as a sink via valine degradation rather than as an asserted productive valine source. Surface reactions explicitly include required mineral agents and are used to model cyanide-bearing ponds, evaporative concentration, photochemistry, and wet-dry processing. Ten distinct pathways to valine are enumerated by combining the retained productive route families and experimentally unresolved but literature-carried branch combinations, while preserving the evidence hierarchy and noting speculation where unavoidable.\n\nMOLECULES (17 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CH4 (methane) [starting]\n  - mol_002: C4H10 (isobutane) [starting]\n  - mol_003: N2 (nitrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_004: NH3 (ammonia) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: H2O (water) [starting]\n  - mol_006: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: C4H8O (isobutyraldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C5H1