ork", "Add an intermediate precursor pool node instead of asserting direct formation of isobutyraldehyde"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_006": 0.52, "rxn_003": 0.82, "rxn_004": 0.74}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.67, "pathway_coherence": 0.72, "environmental_progression": 0.63, "target_achievement": 0.81, "overall_confidence": 0.69, "feedback": "Weak pathway. The literature supports mixed-ice VUV chemistry for amino-acid precursor formation generally, but valine-specific support is contested and the network overstates direct production of both HCN and isobutyraldehyde from this residue. Also, classifying this as Surface chemistry is environmentally inaccurate relative to the cited ice-analog literature.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_004"], "suggestions": ["Reclassify the route as extraterrestrial/ice-analog precursor input rather than a standard surface pond reaction", "Replace direct isobutyraldehyde output with a less specific organic residue or precursor pool"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_007": 0.3, "rxn_008": 0.15, "rxn_009": 0.35}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.27, "pathway_coherence": 0.42, "environmental_progression": 0.46, "target_achievement": 0.54, "overall_confidence": 0.36, "feedback": "This is the weakest major route. Hydrothermal pyruvate formation from only CO2 and H2 is oversimplified and not valine-specific. Conversion of pyruvate to 2-ketoisovalerate is unsupported as a one-step biochemical transformation in this network, and direct amination of 2-ketoisovalerate to valine remains unresolved in the literature. This pathway should be treated as a hypothesis branch, not a credible production route.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "suggestions": ["Do not present this as a productive hydrothermal pathway without explicit caveats", "Add missing branched-chain buildup chemistry or remove the direct pyruvate-to-KIV conversion", "Mark KIV aminat