nce >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Valine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network follows the literature-backed valine evidence bundle by centering productive target formation on three route families: (i) spark-discharge atmospheric synthesis, strongest for isobutane-fed and methane-fed experiments from Ring & Miller (1984); (ii) the chemically grounded but non-quantified Strecker sequence through isobutyraldehyde and valine aminonitrile; and (iii) the hypothesis-level but source-supported \u03b1-ketoacid amination branch through 2-ketoisovalerate. Shock chemistry and VUV-ice photochemistry are included conservatively as precursor-generating or weak direct target-forming routes exactly as constrained by the literature. Hydrothermal chemistry is treated primarily as contextual interconnection and as a destructive constraint on free valine rather than as a strong productive source, consistent with the research findings. To satisfy the required environmental architecture without contradicting the literature, hydrothermal reactions in this graph provide connected carbon/nitrogen feedstocks and a degradation sink, while surface reactions host Strecker, spark-trap, shock, and photochemical concentration/hydrolysis steps. Biochemical/prebiotic reactions capture downstream oligomerization and weakly supported metabolism-like amination. The ten pathways to valine are generated by combining the six direct literature-retained target-forming route families with distinct feeder variants converging on the same validated hubs: isobutyraldehyde, valine aminonitrile, 2-ketoisovalerate, and valine.\n\nMOLECULES (17 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: NH3 (ammonia) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: H2O (water) [starting]\n  - mol_005: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: C4H10 (isobut