 Life and Evolution of the Biosphere*; Table I (isobutane experiment row)**.\n- **Second yield-backed route:** **VAL-R4**, spark discharge with methane feed, with normalized yield **0.00204 % carbon basis for baseline CH4 run (inferred from 0.12% \u00d7 1.7/100)**; citation/locator: **Ring & Miller 1984, *Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere*; Table I (CH4 baseline, CH4-A/B/C, and CH4-80\u00b0 rows)**.\n\nAll other retained routes remain important for mechanistic or environmental context, but in the validated bundle they are **not yield-backed for valine specifically**. The Strecker sequence from **isobutyraldehyde \u2192 valine aminonitrile \u2192 valine** is chemically well grounded and source-supported, yet **no valine-specific numeric yield** was recovered. **Shock synthesis**, **ice/VUV photochemistry**, **2-ketoisovalerate amination**, **dry/high-pressure oligomerization**, and **hydrothermal degradation** are all retained, but mostly as qualitative routes, hypotheses, or sink/constraint processes rather than quantitatively established productive valine syntheses.\n\nThe consolidated network contains **9 precursor/intermediate species**, **9 reaction rows**, **6 direct target-forming routes**, **1 on-path intermediate route**, **2 sink/constraint routes**, and **4 inferred links**. The main unresolved gaps are that only **2/9 routes** are yield-backed, and **hydrothermal, meteoritic, mineral/metal, and ice-UV families remain weakly quantified or source-access-limited**.\n\n## 2. Ranked route table\nYield-backed routes are listed first and explicitly flagged, followed by all remaining retained routes. Values, wording, citations, and locators are carried from validated s6 without alteration.\n\n| Rank | Route ID | Yield-backed? | Route / route type | Precursors | T | P | pH | Catalyst / agents | Phase / medium | Environment | Yield | Citation + exact locator |\n|---|---:|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | VAL-R3 | **FLAGGED** | Spark d