window not valine-specifically resolved` | `NH3/NH4+, HCN/CN\u2212` | `aqueous or mixed aqueous` | `cyanide-bearing pond, evaporative lagoon, meteoritic parent-body aqueous setting, or impact-generated aqueous niche` | `yield not reported (source: VAL-R1-primary-unrecovered; locations checked: full text + SI unavailable in workspace/source-list context)` | `Prebiotic syntheses of vitamin coenzymes: II. Pantoic acid ...; Gargaud et al. 2022 Encyclopedia of Astrobiology; Strecker reaction and \u03b1-aminonitriles 2018 Tetrahedron; locator: yield not reported (source: VAL-R1-primary-unrecovered; locations checked: full text + SI unavailable in workspace/source-list context)` |\n| 4 | VAL-R2 | No | Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine / Strecker hydrolysis | valine aminonitrile + H2O | `105 \u00b0C (laboratory hydrolysis analogue)` | `not reported` | `acidic during laboratory hydrolysis; prebiotic hydrolysis unresolved` | `water; acid in laboratory hydrolysis analogues` | `aqueous` | `aqueous post-synthesis hydrolysis setting` | `yield not reported (source: VAL-R2-primary-unrecovered; locations checked: full text + SI unavailable in workspace/source-list context)` | `Strecker reaction and \u03b1-aminonitriles 2018 Tetrahedron; Gargaud et al. 2022; valine_strecker_isobutyraldehyde_sources.json procedural hits; locator: yield not reported (source: VAL-R2-primary-unrecovered; locations checked: full text + SI unavailable in workspace/source-list context)` |\n| 5 | VAL-R5 | No | Shock synthesis in reduced gas mixture / shock synthesis | CH4 + C2H6 + NH3 + H2O | `transient high-T shock; exact value not extracted` | `transient high-P shock; exact value not extracted` | `not reported` | `shock wave energy` | `gas mixture / primitive-environment simulation` | `impact/shock chemistry in primitive atmosphere or atmosphere-ocean interface` | `yield not reported (source: Bar-Nun-1970-primary-unrecovered; locations checked: full text unavailable; secondary summary in Ring & Miller 1984 + source-list context)` | `Bar-Nun et al. 1970 Nature, as summarized in Ring & Miller 1984 and valine_general_sources.json; locator: yield not reported (source: Bar-Nun-1970-primary-unrecovered; locations checked: full text unavailable; secondary summary in Ring & Miller 1984 + source-list context)` |\n| 6 | VAL-R6 | No | VUV photochemistry of mixed ices followed by hydrolysis / surface-UV / ice photochemistry | H2O + CO + CO2 + CH3OH + CH4 + NH3 mixed ices + acid hydrolysis | `10\u201380 K irradiation; warm-up to room temperature; hydrolysis 105 \u00b0C for 24 h` | `static vacuum ~10^-5 mbar during residue handling` | `2.2 analytical buffer; 6 M HCl hydrolysis in workflow` | `VUV photons; acid hydrolysis; cation-exchange LC detection` | `cryogenic ice then residue then aqueous hydrolysate` | `interstellar/cometary ice analogues` | `yield not reported (source: Nuevo-2008; locations checked: full text Table 1/text + no SI recovered; total amino acids 2.8\u201359.0 nmol reported, but valine-specific quantity not recovered)` | `Nuevo et al. 2008, Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres; Bernstein et al. 2002 Nature; Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. 2002 Nature; locator: yield not reported (source: Nuevo-2008; locations checked: full text Table 1/text + no SI recovered; total amino acids 2.8\u201359.0 nmol reported, but valine-specific quantity not recovered)` |\n| 7 | VAL-R7 | No | \u03b1-ketoacid amination from 2-ketoisovalerate / \u03b1-ketoacid amination / 2-ketoisovalerate | 2-ketoisovalerate + nitrogen donor/reductant | `not reported` | `not reported` | `not reported` | `cyanate in general \u03b1-ketoacid route; possible reducing equivalents/dinucleotide-like catalysts discussed` | `aqueous` | `metabolism-like aqueous network / moderate pond or non-extreme hydrothermal fringe` | `yield not reported (source: VAL-R7-direct-prebiotic-demo-unrecovered; locations checked: full text + SI/source-list context for Liu 2022 and related route papers)` | `Liu et al. 2022 Nature Chemistry; 2021 Life computational analysis; Drotman et al. 1972 Comp. Biochem. Physiol. B; locator: yield not reported (source: VAL-R7-direct-prebiotic-demo-unrecovered; locations checked: full text + SI/source-list context for Liu 2022 and related route papers)` |\n| 8 | VAL-R8 | No | Dry/high-pressure oligomerization of valine / dry/high-pressure diagenetic oligomerization | valine (solid, non-aqueous) | `150\u2013200 \u00b0C` | `50\u2013150 MPa` | `not applicable / non-aqueous` | `none reported` | `non-aqueous solid-state / dehydrating` | `deep prebiotic marine sediments undergoing diagenesis` | `yield not reported (source: 10.1007/s11084-012-9295-0; locations checked: full text Figures 1-3 + corresponding results/discussion text; SI not recovered; paperAnalyzer analyze_pdf attempted on Springer PDF and failed with tool-side 401 auth error)` | `Furukawa, Otake, Ishiguro, Nakazawa & Kakegawa 2012, Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres; locator: yield not reported (source: 10.1007/s11084-012-9295-0; locations checked: full text Figures 1-3 + corresponding results/discussion text; SI not recovered; paperAnalyzer analyze_pdf attempted on Springer PDF and failed with tool-side 401 auth error)` |\n| 9 | VAL-R9 | No | Hydrothermal degradation of valine in subcritical water / hydrothermal degradation | valine in subcritical water | `290\u2013330 \u00b0C` | `subcritical water conditions; exact P not extracted` | `not reported` | `hot compressed water` | `aqueous subcritical water` | `hydrothermal / high-temperature aqueous system` | `yield not reported (source: Kobayashi-2010-primary-unrecovered; locations checked: source-list context/review summary; full text + SI not recovered)` | `Kobayashi, Takase & Adachi 2010 Bioscience, Biotechnology, and Biochemistry; ChemSusChem 2021 review; locator: yield not reported (source: Kobayashi-2010-primary-unrecovered; locations checked: source-list context/review summary; full text + SI not recovered)` |\n\n## 3. Per-route narrative\n\n### VAL-R3 \u2014 Spark discharge with isobutane feed\nThis is the strongest route in the validated bundle because it is one of only two routes with a numeric valine yield carried through s6. The route uses **isobutane + N2 + NH3 + H2O** in a spark-discharge system with **tungsten electrodes**, an **NH4Cl aqueous trap**, and **post-run 3 M HCl hydrolysis**. Reported conditions are `~25 \u00b0C bulk flask; localized spark much hotter`, `N2 80 torr; hydrocarbon 150 torr; water vapor ~25 torr`, and `pH 8.7 (0.05 M NH4Cl adjusted with ~1 mL 1 M NaOH)`. The exact yield text retained is: `valine/glycine mole ratio 34.0; glycine yield 0.036% based on carbon; inferred valine yield \u22480.01224% based on carbon`, normalized as `0.01224 % carbon basis (inferred from 0.036% \u00d7 34.0/100)`, from **Ring & Miller 1984, *Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere*; Table I (isobutane experiment row)**. The validated s6 note adds that the authors interpret the relatively high valine yield with isobutane as arising via oxidation to **isobutyraldehyde hydrate** followed by **Strecker synthesis**.\n\n### VAL-R4 \u2014 Spark discharge with methane feed\nThis is the second yield-backed route. It uses **CH4 + N2 + NH3 + H2O** with **electric spark**, **tungsten electrodes**, **0.05 M NH4Cl solution**, and **post-run 3 M HCl hydrolysis**. Conditions retained are `25 \u00b0C bulk flask in CH4-A/B/C; ~80 \u00b0C in CH4-80\u00b0 experiment`, `CH4 300 torr; N2 80 torr; NH3 0.02, 0.5, or 2.5 torr; water vapor ~25 torr at 25 \u00b0C and ~350 torr at 80 \u00b0C`, and `baseline NH4Cl solution adjusted to pH 8.7`. The exact yield text is `baseline methane experiment: valine/glycine ratio 1.7; glycine yield 0.12% based on carbon; inferred valine yield \u22480.00204% based on carbon. CH4-A/B/C relative valine ratios 1.0, 2.7, 10.2. CH4-80\u00b0 relative valine ratio 0.061 with glycine yield 1.02%.`, normalized as `0.00204 % carbon basis for baseline CH4 run (inferred from 0.12% \u00d7 1.7/100)`, from **Ring & Miller 1984, *Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere*; Table I (CH4 baseline, CH4-A/B/C, and CH4-80\u00b0 rows)**. In the validated ranking, this route is weaker than VAL-R3 because valine is minor in methane-only spark runs relative to isobutane-fed runs.\n\n### VAL-R1 \u2014 Strecker formation of valine aminonitrile from isobutyraldehyde\nThis route maps the first half of a classical Strecker sequence: **isobutyraldehyde + NH3/NH4+ + HCN/CN\u2212 \u2192 valine aminonitrile**. The validated table gives `aqueous or mixed aqueous` medium, `near-neutral to mildly basic/acidic window not valine-specifically resolved`, and no reported T or P. The environmental framing retained is `cyanide-bearing pond, evaporative lagoon, meteoritic parent-body aqueous setting, or impact-generated aqueous niche`. The route is **source-supported**, but the yield field is explicitly `yield not reported (source: VAL-R1-primary-unrecovered; locations checked: full text + SI unavailable in workspace/source-list context)`. The validated synthesis memo ranks the Strecker sequence as chemically well grounded but not quantitatively established for valine in the accepted bundle.\n\n### VAL-R2 \u2014 Hydrolysis of valine aminonitrile to valine\nThis is the second half of the Strecker sequence: **valine aminonitrile + H2O \u2192 valine**. The retained conditions are `aqueous`, `105 \u00b0C (laboratory hydrolysis analogue)`, `acidic during laboratory hydrolysis; prebiotic hydrolysis unresolved`, and `24 h (laboratory hydrolysis analogue)`. The route is treated as a generic, source-supported Strecker conversion, but again the yield is explicitly `yield not reported (source: VAL-R2-primary-unrecovered; locations checked: full text + SI unavailable in workspace/source-list context)`. In the validated bundle, this route remains plausible but quantitatively unresolved under prebiotic conditions.\n\n### VAL-R5 \u2014 Shock synthesis in reduced gas mixture\nThis route uses **CH4 + C2H6 + NH3 + H2O** under **shock wave energy** in a `gas mixture / primitive-environment simulation`. The retained conditions are only qualitative: `transient high-T shock; exact value not extracted` and `transient high-P shock; exact value not extracted`. The environmental interpretation is `impact/shock chemistry in primitive atmosphere or atmosphere-ocean interface`. The validated note states that secondary sources say valine was among products, but no numeric valine yield was recovered. Accordingly, the yield remains `yield not reported (source: Bar-Nun-1970-primary-unrecovered; locations checked: full text unavailable; secondary summary in Ring & Miller 1984 + source-list context)`.\n\n### VAL-R6 \u2014 VUV photochemistry of mixed ices followed by hydrolysis\nThis route represents **surface-UV / ice photochemistry** in mixed ices containing **H2O, CO, CO2, CH3OH, CH4, NH3**, followed by hydrolysis. Retained conditions are `10\u201380 K irradiation; warm-up to room temperature; hydrolysis 105 \u00b0C for 24 h`, `static vacuum ~10^-5 mbar during residue handling`, and `2.2 analytical buffer; 6 M HCl hydrolysis in workflow`, with `VUV photons; acid hydrolysis; cation-exchange LC detection`. The environment is `interstellar/cometary ice analogues`. The validated route table preserves the statement that `amino acids formed in all experiments; total amino acids in hydrolysed residues ranged from 2.8 to 59.0 nmol across experiments; valine included in analytical standard, but valine-specific quantity not extracted from accessible PDF`. Therefore the valine yield is explicitly `yield not reported (source: Nuevo-2008; locations checked: full text Table 1/text + no SI recovered; total amino acids 2.8\u201359.0 nmol reported, but valine-specific quantity not recovered)`. The validated s6 synthesis also flags a contradiction: route-family support is robust, but **valine-specific support is weaker and contested**.\n\n### VAL-R7 \u2014 \u03b1-ketoacid amination from 2-ketoisovalerate\nThis route is framed as **2-ketoisovalerate + nitrogen donor/reductant \u2192 valine** in an `aqueous` setting, with `cyanate in general \u03b1-ketoacid route; possible reducing equivalents/dinucleotide-like catalysts discussed`. The environment is `metabolism-like aqueous network / moderate pond or non-extreme hydrothermal fringe`. However, T, P, and pH are all `not reported`, and the yield is explicitly `yield not reported (source: VAL-R7-direct-prebiotic-demo-unrecovered; locations checked: full text + SI/source-list context for Liu 2022 and related route papers)`. The validated s6 synthesis treats this route as **mechanistically attractive but still hypothesis/inference**, not a direct demonstrated enzyme-free prebiotic valine route.\n\n### VAL-R8 \u2014 Dry/high-pressure oligomerization of valine\nThis route is retained because it is experimentally relevant to valine\u2019s fate, but the validated bundle treats it as a **sink/assembly route from valine**, not a productive route to free valine. Conditions are `150\u2013200 \u00b0C`, `50\u2013150 MPa`, `not applicable / non-aqueous`, `48\u2013192 h`, and `non-aqueous solid-state / dehydrating`, in `deep prebiotic marine sediments undergoing diagenesis`. The route table explicitly gives `yield not reported` for the s4y-compliant route row because exact page-level locator verification for numeric values was not available under the task rules. At the network level, however, the validated note records that `linear peptide yields 0.19\u20130.36% at 48 h, decreasing to 0.07\u20130.16% at 192 h; at 200 \u00b0C and 100 MPa for 192 h, NH3 yield up to 20% and glycine yield up to 0.015%; higher pressure preserved more residual valine and peptides`. The validated contradictions table explicitly states that VAL-R8 should be interpreted separately from productive synthesis routes.\n\n### VAL-R9 \u2014 Hydrothermal degradation of valine in subcritical water\nThis route is also a **constraint/sink**, not a productive synthesis route. Conditions are `290\u2013330 \u00b0C`, `subcritical water conditions; exact P not extracted`, `aqueous subcritical water`, and `hot compressed water`, in a `hydrothermal / high-temperature aqueous system`. The validated route row states `degradation kinetics reported; numeric rate constants not extracted because primary paper was not accessed`, and the yield is explicitly `yield not reported (source: Kobayashi-2010-primary-unrecovered; locations checked: source-list context/review summary; full text + SI not recovered)`. In the validated ranking, this route is retained mainly to constrain environmental plausibility by showing that many hydrothermal settings may destroy free valine rather than accumulate it.\n\n## 4. Intermediates and precursors\nThe consolidated precursor network contains **9 species**. The key retained intermediates and precursors are:\n\n- **isobutyraldehyde** \u2014 `direct Strecker aldehyde precursor to valine`; evidence status `source-supported`; citation basis: `Prebiotic syntheses of vitamin coenzymes: II. Pantoic acid ... (J. Mol. Evol.; source-list note); Gargaud et al. 2022 Encyclopedia of Astrobiology; Strecker reaction and \u03b1-aminonitriles review 2018 Tetrahedron`.\n- **valine aminonitrile (2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile)** \u2014 `immediate Strecker intermediate between isobutyraldehyde and valine`; evidence status `source-supported`; citation basis: `valine_strecker_isobutyraldehyde_sources.json procedural hits; Strecker review 2018 Tetrahedron`.\n- **NH3/NH4+** \u2014 `nitrogen donor in Strecker and \u03b1-ketoacid amination routes`; evidence status `source-supported`; citation basis: `Ring & Miller 1984 Origins Life Evol Biosph; Gargaud et al. 2022`.\n- **HCN/CN\u2212** \u2014 `cyanide nucleophile enabling aminonitrile formation`; evidence status `source-supported`; citation basis: `Gargaud et al. 2022; Strecker reaction and \u03b1-aminonitriles review 2018 Tetrahedron`.\n- **2-ketoisovalerate (KIV)** \u2014 `\u03b1-ketoacid precursor to valine`; evidence status `source-supported but valine-specific prebiotic conversion not directly demonstrated`; `inferred_link = True`; citation basis: `Liu et al. 2022 Nature Chemistry; Drotman et al. 1972 Comp. Biochem. Physiol. B; valine_hypotheses.md`.\n- **pyruvate-derived branched \u03b1-ketoacid network** \u2014 `upstream feeder network to KIV`; evidence status `source-supported pathway context`; `inferred_link = True`; citation basis: `valine_ketoisovalerate_amination_sources.json pathway sources`.\n- **isobutane / higher hydrocarbons** \u2014 `atmospheric/plasma feedstocks whose oxidation can generate valine precursors`; evidence status `source-supported`; `inferred_link = True`; citation basis: `Ring & Miller 1984 Origins Life Evol Biosph`.\n- **mixed ices (H2O, CO, CO2, CH3OH, CH4, NH3)** \u2014 `cosmic-ice feedstocks yielding amino-acid precursors and sometimes valine/valine-like products after VUV processing and hydrolysis`; evidence status `partly source-supported; valine-specific detection contested`; `inferred_link = True`; citation basis: `Bernstein et al. 2002 Nature; Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. 2002 Nature; Nuevo et al. 2008 OLEB; valine_hypotheses.md`.\n- **valine** \u2014 both the target monomer and a precursor to downstream peptide/sink chemistry under dry high-P or hydrothermal conditions; citation basis: `Otake et al. 2012 OLEB; Kobayashi et al. 2010 BBB`.\n\nOverall network summary from validated s6:\n- **Precursors/intermediates consolidated:** 9\n- **Reaction rows consolidated:** 9\n- **Direct target-forming routes:** 6\n- **On-path intermediate routes:** 1\n- **Sink/constraint routes:** 2\n- **Inferred links flagged in network:** 4\n\n## 5. Mineral catalysts and surfaces\nThe validated route table contains limited direct mineral catalysis for productive valine synthesis, but the retained source and precursor bundle does preserve several mineral/surface contexts:\n\n- For the **ice/VUV route (VAL-R6)**, the route table lists **`MgF2 or Cu substrates depending on experiment`** under `mineral_surface`, with the route occurring in `cryogenic ice then residue then aqueous hydrolysate` under `interstellar/cometary ice analogues`.\n- The deduplicated retained source list includes direct mineral/surface entries such as:\n  - **`Infrared spectra of valine adsorbed on Cu-montmorillonite` (1972, American Mineralogist)**, described in the retained relevance note as showing `IR evidence for bidentate chelate and monodentate Cu-valine complexes and pH dependence`.\n  - **`Possible selective adsorption of enantiomers by Na-montmorillonite ...` (1982, NASA NTRS)**, described as a direct valine hit where `racemic valine and norvaline were incubated with Na-montmorillonite and adsorption/enantiomer differences assessed`.\n  - General clay-catalyzed condensation/polymerization background sources such as **`The mechanism of clay catalyzed polymerization of amino acid ...` (1976)** and **`The polymerization of amino acid adenylates on sodium-montmorillonite ...` (1988)**.\n  - Broader Fe/S plausibility context from **`On the prebiotic role of iron and sulfur` (2001)**.\n\nWithin the validated s6 synthesis, these mineral and surface sources are not elevated to productive, yield-backed valine-forming routes. Instead, they support **adsorption, complexation, chiral selection, or condensation context**, while the explicit gap statement says **mineral/metal families remain weakly quantified or source-access-limited**.\n\n## 6. Experimental evidence and environmental context\n### Strongest experimental evidence\nThe strongest direct experimental evidence in the validated bundle is the **spark-discharge family**, especially **isobutane-fed discharge**. Both yield-backed routes come from **Ring & Miller (1984)** and include explicit conditions, quantitative inference, and exact table locators. The validated ranking therefore places **VAL-R3** first and **VAL-R4** second.\n\n### Strecker environmental context\nThe Strecker sequence is mapped onto `cyanide-bearing pond, evaporative lagoon, meteoritic parent-body aqueous setting, or impact-generated aqueous niche`. This makes it environmentally plausible in several prebiotic settings, but the accepted bundle does not recover valine-specific numeric yields for either aminonitrile formation or hydrolysis.\n\n### Shock context\nThe shock route is retained as `impact/shock chemistry in primitive atmosphere or atmosphere-ocean interface`. It is experimentally suggestive but quantitatively unresolved for valine in the validated bundle.\n\n### Ice/UV context\nThe ice photochemistry route is retained for `interstellar/cometary ice analogues`. The validated evidence supports general amino-acid formation strongly, but valine-specific assignment remains weaker. The route therefore contributes environmental plausibility for extraterrestrial or nebular precursor chemistry, but not a quantified valine synthesis yield.\n\n### Dry high-pressure and hydrothermal context\nThe validated bundle treats **dry/high-pressure oligomerization** and **hydrothermal degradation** mainly as **post-formation fate constraints**. Dry, pressurized, water-poor settings can oligomerize valine and generate decomposition products, while hot compressed water can degrade valine. These routes therefore matter for environmental survivability and accumulation, not just synthesis.\n\n### Meteoritic context\nThe validated gaps table preserves the open question: `What fraction of meteoritic valine reflects parent-body Strecker synthesis versus terrestrial contamination or analytical ambiguity?` The deduplicated source list contains many meteoritic records, but the validated synthesis explicitly notes that meteoritic family coverage remains weakly quantified or source-access-limited for this task.\n\n## 7. Open questions and debates\nThe validated s6 gaps/contradictions/open-questions table identifies the following unresolved issues:\n\n### Gaps\n- `Only 2 of 9 routes are yield-backed with numeric values plus citation/locator in s4y (VAL-R3, VAL-R4).`\n- `Hydrothermal, meteoritic, mineral/metal, and ice-UV families remain weakly quantified or source-access-limited; most retained as yield not reported or contested.`\n\n### Contradictions\n- `VAL-R8 is a downstream sink/assembly route from valine, not a synthesis route to free valine, yet appears in the same route bundle; it should be interpreted separately from productive routes.`\n- `Ice-UV route retains valine as contested/weakly assigned in accessible extraction, while general amino-acid formation is robust; valine-specific support is therefore weaker than route-family support.`\n\n### Open questions\n- `Can enzyme-free 2-ketoisovalerate amination produce valine directly under plausible prebiotic conditions with measurable yield?`\n- `Are branched aldehydes such as isobutyraldehyde sufficiently available in relevant prebiotic environments to make Strecker valine competitive with spark-discharge production?`\n- `Do hydrothermal settings ever net-produce valine, or are they predominantly destructive for free valine once formed?`\n- `What fraction of meteoritic valine reflects parent-body Strecker synthesis versus terrestrial contamination or analytical ambiguity?`\n\n## 8. Coverage and source accounting\nThis section reports only the validated s6 accounting.\n\n- **Number of search angles:** 9\n- **Total sources touched:** 191\n- **Total retained:** 52\n- **Raw consolidated source rows:** 485\n- **Deduplicated retained source count:** 439\n\nValidated reconciliation note:\n- `summed_rows_retained` is the sum of retained rows explicitly tallied in upstream accepted search-angle artifacts.\n- `raw_source_rows` is the number of consolidated inherited source rows before deduplication in the accepted s6 aggregation.\n- `deduplicated_source_count` is the post-deduplication unique-source total.\n- The validated s6 note states: `rows_retained and raw_source_rows are not expected to match because they refer to different upstream accounting layers; no accepted source row was intentionally dropped in this patch.`\n\n### Total source count gathered\nUsing the validated s6 accounting, the total deduplicated retained source count gathered for this report is **439**.\n\n### Unresolved coverage gaps\nAs documented upstream and carried forward unchanged:\n- only **2 of 9** routes are yield-backed;\n- **hydrothermal, meteoritic, mineral/metal, and ice-UV** families remain weakly quantified or source-access-limited;\n- some family-level proof and metadata verification remained limited by source access/platform constraints already documented upstream.\n\n## 9. Reference list cited in the report\nOnly sources explicitly cited in validated s6 content are listed here.\n\n- Bar-Nun et al. 1970. *Nature*.\n- Bernstein, Dworkin, Sandford, Cooper, Allamandola. 2002. *Nature*.\n- Drotman, Featherston, Freedland. 1972. *Comparative Biochemistry and Physiology B*.\n- Furukawa, Otake, Ishiguro, Nakazawa, Kakegawa. 2012. *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*.\n- Gargaud et al. 2022. *Encyclopedia of Astrobiology*.\n- Kobayashi, Takase, Adachi. 2010. *Bioscience, Biotechnology, and Biochemistry*.\n- Liu et al. 2022. *Nature Chemistry*.\n- Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. 2002. *Nature*.\n- Nuevo et al. 2008. *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*.\n- Prebiotic syntheses of vitamin coenzymes: II. Pantoic acid ... Year and journal details as retained in validated source context: *J. Mol. Evol.*\n- Ring, Miller. 1984. *Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere*.\n- Strecker reaction and \u03b1-aminonitriles. 2018. *Tetrahedron*.\n- ChemSusChem review. 2021. *ChemSusChem*.\n\n### Complete deduplicated retained source list artifact\nThe complete deduplicated retained source list for the validated s6 bundle is available as the companion artifact:\n- `valine_complete_deduplicated_sources.csv`\n\nThis report does not add or alter any source rows beyon